  • Look at a boxplot of expression values for each sample and see whether any seem to be outliers.
boxplot(raw.data, col="red", main="Raw Probe Intensities")

None of the samples are outliers based on this plot.

  • Perform RMA on the samples and create a new intensity boxplot.
GSE27973.rma <- rma(raw.data)
## Background correcting
## Normalizing
## Calculating Expression
boxplot(exprs(GSE27973.rma), col="blue", main="RMA Expression Values")

The intensity distribution of each sample is very similar now. The mean, range, and overall distribution of intensities across samples is uniform.

  • Perform a differential expression analysis, and report how many probes are significantly differentially expressed between the CSE and medium samples based on a Benjamini-Hochberg corrected p-value threshold of 0.05.
design <- model.matrix(~ -1+factor(GSE27973.rma$treatment))
colnames(design) <- levels(factor(GSE27973.rma$treatment))
fit <- lmFit(GSE27973.rma, design)
#Note: we only need one contrast to get the results of interest
GSE27973.contrast <- makeContrasts(smoke=CSE-medium, levels = design)
fit2 <- contrasts.fit(fit, GSE27973.contrast)
fit2 <- eBayes(fit2)

smoke_results <- topTable(fit2, coef="smoke" , adjust="BH", p.value=0.05, number=100)

smoke_results$ID = row.names(smoke_results)
smoke_results$SYMBOL <- lapply(smoke_results$ID, function(x) mget(x, env=hgu133plus2SYMBOL, ifnotfound=NA)[[1]])
smoke_results

  • What is the top differentially expressed gene? Create a boxplot of its normalized intensities across all treatment groups. How many probes corresponding to this gene are among the top hits?
library(ggplot2)
df_boxplot=data.frame(
  expression=exprs(GSE27973.rma)["201468_s_at", ],
  status=GSE27973.rma$treatment)

ggplot(df_boxplot, aes(x=status, y=expression)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.colour=NA, color="grey18", fill="lightgreen") +
  stat_boxplot(geom='errorbar', color="grey18") +
  geom_jitter(size=1, position=position_jitter(width=0.3)) +
  ggtitle("Boxplot for probe 201468_s_at") +
  xlab("")+
  ylab("RMA-intensity")+
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position="none")

The top differentially expressed gene is NQO1. Three probes for this gene are among the top hits.

  • Create a heatmap using the significantly differentially expressed genes and samples from all conditions. How do the treatment groups cluster? What does this indicate (a qualitative answer is sufficient)?
library(gplots)
top.eset <- GSE27973.rma[row.names(exprs(GSE27973.rma)) %in% row.names(smoke_results)]
four.col <- c("red", "lightgrey", "blue", "darkorchid4")
status.colors <- sapply(as.numeric(factor(GSE27973.rma$treatment)), function(x) {four.col[x]})
heatmap.2(exprs(top.eset), col=viridis(256, option="B"),
          trace="none", keysize=1.5, key.title=NA, cexRow=0.8,
          ColSideColors=status.colors)
legend("topright", legend = c("CSE", "medium", "RV16", "RV16_CSE"), 
    fill=four.col, cex=0.5)

The differential expression of genes in the two treatments that involve CSE exposure is similar (at least for this set of genes), while the control and rhinovirus samples are more similar to each other. Thus, for this set of genes, rhinovirus does not influence the expression of CSE-modified genes.
